---> PRESENT PERFECT TENSE
HAS
Q --> has he/she (ever) been in Madrid?
A --> yes, he/she has been in Madrid
N --> no, he/she has not/(never) been in Madrid
HAVE
Q --> have you (ever) been in Madrid?
A --> yes, I have been in Madrid
N --> no, I have not/(never) been in Madrid

	Present Perfect Signals: 
		for 		(-dır, -dir)				- he has been abroad for eight years
		since		(-den beri)				- Olympics have been held since 1896 / for hundred twenty five years
		already 	(zaten, çoktan)				- we have already seen this method work
		still		(halen)					- I still haven’t reached my aim.
		just 		( + henüz, yeni, demin)			- they may have just moved to Birmingham from another city
		yet		( - henüz)				- I haven’t made up my mind, I have not yet had time to settle down!
		always 		(her zaman)				- you always have been next to me and you always will be
		so far		(şimdiye kadar)				- his ideas have become so far part of the common thought of the time
		up to now	(şimdiye kadar)				- he has mended many cars up to now
		until now	(şimdiye kadar)				- he has met with some highly people until now
		lately		(geçenlerde, son zamanlarda)		- have you seen her lately? (not past simple)
		recently	(son zamnalarda, yakınlarda)		- a new school has recently opened in New Road
		never		(- hiç)					- I've never thought about it before
		ever		(+ hiç)					- haven't you ever made a mistake?  
									- you're the first girl who has ever accepted me for what I am.
		how long	(ne kadar süre) 			- exactly. How long have you been married?
		today 		(bugün)					- today has been quite breezy, which I love
		this morning/week/month/year				- I’ve written three letters this morning.
		this term						- he hasn’t studied very hard this term
		over the past/last few years		 		- prices have fallen sharply over the past six months
		during the past/last few years				- he leased space by agreement with many companies during the last few months
		in the past/last few years				- I’ve met a lot of people in the last few days.
		before							- nothing like this has happened before
	 


present perfect	dı, di		I have lost my wallet	lately (belli değil, etkisi halen var ki bu muhabbeti bana)
past simple	dı, di		I lost my wallet 	yesterday (olmuş bitmiş)

past perfect	mış, miş	I had lost my wallet
						
					eylem öncelliği
						1. eylem
						2. eylem
			 
			 	cüzdanımı kaybetmiştim, .... ağladım.
				1				2
				after I had lost my purse, I cried
				
				before I cried, I had lost my purse
				
		 		after 1, 2
				before 2, 1
				

